      "id": "cp_nernst2_001",
      "passage": "A chemistry lab builds galvanic cells using Zn/Zn\u00b2\u207a and Cu/Cu\u00b2\u207a half-cells connected by a salt bridge. Under standard conditions, the cell produces a positive voltage and drives electrons through a wire from zinc to copper. Students then vary ion concentrations and observe that cell voltage changes even though the electrodes are made from the same metals.\n\nCondition | [Zn\u00b2\u207a] | [Cu\u00b2\u207a] | Measured cell voltage\nStandard | 1.0 M | 1.0 M | 1.10 V\nHigh Zn\u00b2\u207a | 10 M | 1.0 M | lower\nHigh Cu\u00b2\u207a | 1.0 M | 10 M | higher\n\nThe instructor summarizes the reaction as Zn(s) + Cu\u00b2\u207a(aq) \u2192 Zn\u00b2\u207a(aq) + Cu(s).",
      "stem": "Which species is oxidized in the galvanic cell?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Cu\u00b2\u207a(aq)"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Zn(s)"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Cu(s)"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "The salt bridge ions only"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Cu\u00b2\u207a gains electrons to form Cu(s), so it is reduced rather than oxidized.",
        "B": "Correct. Zinc metal loses electrons to form Zn\u00b2\u207a, so it is oxidized. Those electrons travel through the external circuit toward the copper half-cell.",
        "C": "Copper metal is the reduction product in the stated spontaneous reaction, not the reactant being oxidized.",
        "D": "Salt bridge ions maintain charge balance but are not the redox species in the net reaction."
      },
      "topic": "Electrochemistry II: Nernst Equation & Batteries",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageImage": "data:image/png;base64,"
    },
    {
