    {
      "id": "cp_nernst2_006",
      "passage": "A medical-device company tests a miniature battery for an implant. The battery must supply steady current at body temperature, but internal resistance causes terminal voltage to drop under high load. During discharge, reactants are consumed and products accumulate, gradually lowering the driving force. The team distinguishes electrolytic cells, which require external electrical energy, from galvanic cells, which produce electrical energy from spontaneous redox reactions.",
      "stem": "Why does terminal voltage drop under high load in the implant battery?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "The redox reaction stops being chemical"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "The battery becomes an ideal voltage source"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Internal resistance causes an IR drop inside the battery"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "The electrodes have no resistance or polarization"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "The battery remains a chemical redox device; high load changes voltage losses, not the nature of the reaction.",
        "B": "An ideal voltage source would maintain terminal voltage regardless of load, which is the opposite of the observed drop.",
        "C": "Correct. Real batteries have internal resistance and kinetic limitations. When current is high, voltage lost inside the cell increases, so terminal voltage delivered to the device falls.",
        "D": "If there were no resistance or polarization, high load would not lower terminal voltage as described."
      },
      "topic": "Electrochemistry II: Nernst Equation & Batteries",
      "difficulty": "Medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_nernst2_007",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "During discharge, why does voltage gradually fall?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Reactants are consumed and products accumulate, reducing redox driving force"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Products become reactants with infinite voltage"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "The battery gains unlimited Gibbs free energy"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Current changes into mass"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. As discharge proceeds, the reaction quotient shifts toward products. That reduces the thermodynamic driving force and therefore cell voltage.",
        "B": "Products accumulating generally lowers the forward driving force; it does not create infinite voltage.",
        "C": "A discharging battery loses available free energy. It does not gain unlimited \u0394G for useful work.",
        "D": "Current is charge flow, not mass conversion. The voltage decline follows chemical composition and internal losses."
      },
      "topic": "Electrochemistry II: Nernst Equation & Batteries",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "passageRef": "cp_nernst2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_nernst2_008",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Which cell type requires external electrical energy to drive a nonspontaneous reaction?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "A salt bridge alone"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Galvanic cell"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "A fully discharged ideal cell producing power forever"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Electrolytic cell"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "D",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "A salt bridge is not a complete electrochemical cell and cannot drive a redox reaction alone.",
        "B": "A galvanic cell is spontaneous as written and produces electrical energy, at least until reactants are depleted.",
        "C": "A fully discharged cell cannot produce power forever; that violates the chemical limitation described in the passage.",
        "D": "Correct. An electrolytic cell uses external electrical work to drive a nonspontaneous redox reaction. That distinguishes it from a galvanic cell, which generates electrical energy from a spontaneous reaction."
      },
      "topic": "Electrochemistry II: Nernst Equation & Batteries",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "cp_nernst2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
